two catch block(1 general,1 specific) why it is not possible?

Java follows top-down exception matching:

It checks catch blocks from top to bottom
Once a match is found → remaining blocks are ignored
try {
    int a = 10 / 0;
}
catch (Exception e) {              // General exception
    System.out.println("General Exception");
}
catch (ArithmeticException e) {    // Specific exception
    System.out.println("Arithmetic Exception");
}
ArithmeticException is a subclass of Exception
The first catch (Exception e) already handles ALL exceptions
So the second catch block will never execute

This leads to a compile-time error.